  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Los Angeles with three kids and a busy schedule, I’ve learned that fake content on social media isn’t just a distraction—it’s a real problem. I’ve seen too many people, especially moms like me, get caught up in viral trends that promise quick fixes but end up causing more harm than good. For instance, a few years ago, I was scrolling through Instagram and saw a post claiming a 30-day diet could make you lose 20 pounds without any effort. I knew right away it was fake because it didn’t match the science I’ve learned from my own training and the health advice I give my clients. My kids’ safety is my top priority, so I’ve made it a habit to check the credibility of posts before sharing them. I also rely on my family’s support—my wife and kids help me stay grounded by reminding me to focus on real, sustainable habits instead of quick fixes. Another thing that helps is being mindful of my own habits. I’m not the type to get easily overwhelmed by social media, but I’ve noticed that when I’m stressed, I tend to click more on sensational content. That’s why I’ve started setting specific times to check my feeds, like after my morning workouts or during my cooking sessions. It’s important to remember that in this digital age, not everything you see is true. My Hindu background teaches me to question things before acting, and that’s something I try to apply to my online presence too. Ultimately, managing fake content isn’t about avoiding social media—it’s about being smart and responsible, especially when you’re a parent who wants the best for your family.",
